xwikidoc.content:
= Adding a new language =
There are two processes to add a new language, depending on if you want to submit an initial translation file (ApplicationResources) or if you want to start from scratch directly on l10n.xwiki.org.
== Add new language ==
1. Create a JIRA issue on http://jira.xwiki.org/browse/XINFRA to request adding a new language to http://l10n.xwiki.org. 1. Once the team added the new language you can go on http://l10n.xwiki.org and start adding translations. You can either use key by key translation UI or import a whole translation file directly using batch import. Usually for a new language the batch import is used because there is a lot of keys and you will probably want to translate the whole thing and test it before putting it on http://l10n.xwiki.org. Note that importing at once so many translations can take a while so don't worry if your browser give you timeout error, the process still continue behind the scene (the UI need to be improved to get a nice progress bar etc.).
== Translate and test an ApplicationResources file ==
For this you need to:
1. Download the ApplicationResources file in english language. It's here for XE: https://github.com/xwiki/xwiki-platform/blob/master/xwiki-platform-core/xwiki-platform-oldcore/src/main/resources/ApplicationResources.properties 1. Translate it. Beware that you need to use special encoding for non ASCII chars and the file encoding has to be ISO 8859-1. You might want to lookup on the internet for tools to help you out for this, see Native2Ascii for example. To quickly test it you can do the following: 1*. name you file based on the language (for example ApplicationResources_fr.properties for French) 1*. place in into WEB-INF/classes folder 1*. change the default language in the General section of your wiki administration
== XWiki team only ==
Once it's committed the xwiki.org team will very probably do the following steps:
1. Edit the main page of the application. For XE use: {{velocity}}$xwiki.getURL("XE.WebHome", "inline"){{/velocity}}. 1. Add to the list of translation the language code at the end of the list of available languages ( ,fr for French). {{warning}}The language code is the standard format use in JAVA which mean [[<language code~>>>http://ftp.ics.uci.edu/pub/ietf/http/related/iso639.txt]]_[[<COUNTRY CODE~>>>http://userpage.chemie.fu-berlin.de/diverse/doc/ISO_3166.html]].{{/warning}} 1. Save. 1. [nice to have] Add the corresponding flag on [[L10N.Flags]] 1. [nice to have] Add the corresponding pretty name on [[L10N.LocaleTranslations]]
